snippet.textDisplay: I'll be 44 soon and this brought a few tears to my eyes.  I have been a fan since I was pretty much born as my dad was a heavy rocker back in the day and I grew up listening to Black Sabbath.  As I got older I was addicted to Ozzy when he started solo.... man it's crazy it's been this long.  I wont lie, thinking about getting old and passing on never bothered me much, until recently.  Coming to grips with your own mortality isn't easy I'm starting to realize, but hey, gotta live a good life and enjoy what you can while you are around.  Keep on rocking Ozzy and thanks for so many decades of awesome music and concerts!

snippet.textDisplay: Followed Ozzy when he left Sabbath. I remember the premier for Blizzard of Oz on late night radio. Diary of a Madman that followed is imo the best album of Ozzy's career. Man it sucks to get old. To see how different things are. Way different. Ozzy used to be hated by the censorers and up tight people, and was blamed for having subliminal lyrics. You'd never hear him on the radio much. MTV didn't play much of his stuff. Except for his hits. As cringe as the Osborne's was seeing Ozzy obviously having issues and the stuttering, and how the young people were making fun of him and watching only to see what ridiculous things they would say and do, broke my heart. However it propelled him in the spot light and with Sharon being a very out spoken person who is on a day time show and others. I'm very happy John Michael Osborne is now a treasured icon. Love ya Oz. Peace✌️
